A '''reference ecosystem''', also known as an '''ecological reference''', is a "[[community (ecology)|community]] of organisms able to act as a model or benchmark for [[ecological restoration|restoration]]."<ref>{{cite report |last1=McDonald |first1=T. |last2=Gann |first2=G. D. |last3=Jonson |first3=J. |last4=Dixon |first4=K. W. |title=International Standards for the Practice of Ecological Restoration - Including Principles and Key Concepts |url=https://c.ymcdn.com/sites/www.ser.org/resource/resmgr/docs/SER_International_Standards.pdf |publisher=Society for Ecological Restoration |accessdate=2018-08-20 |date=2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seraustralasia.com/standards/principle1.html|title=Ecological restoration practice is based on an appropriate local indigenous reference ecosystem|website=www.seraustralasia.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a571264.pdf|title=Reference Concepts in Ecosystem Restoration and Environmental Benefits Analysis (EBA): Principles and Practices|last=Miller|first=Sarah|date=|website=Defense Technical Information Center|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=21 August 2018}}</ref> Reference ecosystems usually include [[remnant natural area]]s which have not been degraded by human activities such as [[agriculture]], [[logging]], [[land development|development]], [[Fire_ecology#Some_examples_of_fire_in_different_ecosystems|fire]] suppression, or [[invasive species|non-native species invasion]]. Reference ecosystems are ideally complete with natural flora, fauna, [[abiotic]] elements, and ecological functions, processes, and [[succession (ecology)|successional]] states. Multiple reference ecosystems may be pieced together to form the model upon which an ecological restoration project may be based.
